Let me think through this step by step...

The key psychological mechanisms involved in responder behavior in this ultimatum game are fairness and self-interest.  Responders will likely weigh the proposed split against their perception of a fair outcome, considering their contribution relative to the opponent's.  A purely self-interested responder would accept any offer greater than zero, while a purely fairness-focused responder would only accept offers perceived as equitable.  Most people fall somewhere between these extremes.


How these mechanisms interact:  A responder's decision likely involves a trade-off between the amount offered and their perception of fairness.  A larger offer might be accepted even if it's considered slightly unfair, while a smaller, fairer offer might be preferred to a larger, unfair one.


What mathematical form could capture these interactions: A utility function can capture this trade-off.  It can include terms representing the monetary value of the offer and a term representing the perceived fairness of the offer.  The fairness term should depend on the relative contributions of the players and the proposed split.


What parameters would be needed to calibrate the model: Two parameters would suffice: One to weight the importance of the monetary gain (self-interest) and one to weight the importance of fairness.


How the model variables map to observable behavior: Higher values for the self-interest parameter will lead to more acceptance of even unfair offers, while higher values for the fairness parameter will lead to more rejection of unfair offers.  The interplay between these parameters will determine the acceptance threshold.  The fairness term could be based on the ratio of proposed shares to relative contributions: (split_self / token_self) / (split_opp / token_opp).  A ratio of 1 indicates perfect fairness (proportionate to contributions).


Given that the model should predict only responder behavior and only calculate the utility of accepting an offer, here's the model:

